questionRound.0.question.9.answer: Predict what is the next player's move. It's a domino effect as each player wants to gain the maximum tokens possible.

My strategies were pretty fair minded  I made an algorithm in my head of all the possibiliteies of how this game would spread out. My conclusion was that the mind had to choose self reward over the rewards to  others. In addition it would also ask which side do you feel needs your help more and how can one formulate a way to maybe try to help both parties on your sides.

I think it depends on a few elements. | Firstly  I think there will be some skills in every game. So after playing a few times  you can be familiar with it and are more likely to get higher scores. | Secondly   I think it depends on the playmates' behavior and luck. | Finally  I think sometimes it's better to think differently when playing the game. And I usually try not to use the same strategies which will be easily understood by others.

After a few rounds  I began working in reverse  starting with the last player's move to mine. I did this because this game is all about cooperation and predicting other players' moves under the assumption that everyone is playing to earn the most payoffs. | I started off with the last player (Green)'s ideal situation  in which he choose Xg for 28 points and Orange chooses Xo  and then figured out how Blue and then Red  and the Orange would react to this decision. This method worked well for me regardless of which player I was.

If I were first to choose  I would always look through all the boxes and predict how the following players would select  especially the last person  since I immediately eliminated two of his or her four boxes. If I were second or third to select  I tried to choose the options that would help the person ahead of me (usually one that wouldn't harm me either). I noticed I didn't always go for the highest number in my payoff boxes because sometimes it was safer to go for the second highest. Other players seemed to punish me with the lower number if I had given the option with the highest number in my own payoff box. Going last in the order of choices was my favorite because I felt that I had most power in my choice. Choosing first  second  or third narrowed down my options from four to two  but allowed another person to decided which one of the two I would receive. However  being last gave me the luxury of choosing one of two at the cost of the first person taking away two of my options before I even got to see them. I liked knowing that I had the power to choose my own payoff by selecting the higher number of the two remaining.

I would figure out which one the other players would pick based on either decision I could make and then decide which way would give me the best outcome. So if I were the first to choose  I'd look at what the last player would choose if I chose X or Y  then the 3rd player  then the second  and look at how much I would make each way.

The last person's choices were pre-determined (i.e. they had one choice that resulted in both the highest point outcomes) and using that each player can determine the others' choices by cascading down the line.
Prisoner's dilemma theory. Tried to act with everyone's best interest in mind

Obviously the person who gets to choose last has the greatest advantage  for he or she can confidently tell which option would maximize his or her payoff  given the choices already decided by other participants. The person who plays before the last one also can surely determine which option offers the most benefits  for he or she knows what the last person would choose  and that selection is what impacts the outcome of the second last player.
I look at the best possible outcomes that other players will choose in which they and myself will gain not the maximum profit but the minimization of the losses.

When I was the first person to pick an action  I started by picking the option that could potentially have the best pay-out for me. Then I went backwards (color 4  color 3  color 2) and assumed each player would choose the best option for themselves (never the lesser amount). If when I made it back to mine  I still had the best amount I could receive  I chose my original action  if I found that my original action did not give me the best result  I chose the other option.

optimize profit: if first player  then predict the consequences of each choice under the assumption that each player will choose higher payoff over lower payoff. if not first player  then predict the choice of the last player as he is affected by the first player's decision  and continue left until i know which payoffs to choose from.
